<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="1623" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1156,1287,1727]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">
<taxonomicName box="[160,401,1287,1311]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[160,401,1287,1311]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">Ambigolimax nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[458,609,1287,1311]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[458,609,1287,1311]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from Los Angeles County could not be reliably differentiated by mantle patterning or the morphology of the radula or jawı a finding that supports the conclusion of authors including 
<bibRefCitation author="Mc Donnell Ri Paine Ti Gormally MJ" box="[826,1103,1357,1381]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" refId="ref13048" refString="Mc Donnell Ri Paine Ti Gormally MJ. 2009. Slugs: A Guide to the Invasive and Native Fauna of California. Oakland (CA): University of California Agriculture and Natural Resources Publ; p. 8336." type="journal volume" year="2009">Mc Donnell et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
and Rowsonı Turnerı et al. (2014b). These taxa could be differentiated by distal genital morphology and COI barcode sequences (
<bibRefCitation author="Nitz Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G" box="[525,687,1426,1450]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="405 - 435" refId="ref13485" refString="Nitz Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G. 2010. Inferring multiple Corsican Limax (Pulmonata: Limacidae) radiations: a combined approach using morphology and molecules. In: Burckhardt Di editor. Evolution in Action. Berlin: Springer. p. 405 - 435." type="book chapter" year="2010">Nitz et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC" box="[699,916,1426,1450]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="91907" refId="ref14178" refString="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC. 2014 a. The slugs of Britain and Ireland: undetected and undescribed species increase a well-studiedi economically important fauna by more than 20 %. PLoS One. 9 (3): e 91907." type="journal article" year="2014">Rowson et al. 2014a</bibRefCitation>
). Such sequence data are not without limitations (
<bibRefCitation author="Davison Ai Blackie RLi Scothern GP" box="[459,663,1461,1485]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="1092 - 1101" refId="ref11153" refString="Davison Ai Blackie RLi Scothern GP. 2009. DNA barcoding of stylommatophoran land snails: a test of existing sequences. Mol Ecol Resour. 9 (4): 1092 - 1101." type="journal article" year="2009">Davison et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sauer Ji Hausdorf B" box="[674,946,1461,1485]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="300 - 316" refId="ref14320" refString="Sauer Ji Hausdorf B. 2012. A comparison of DNA-based methods for delimiting species in a Cretan land snail radiation reveals shortcomings of exclusively molecular taxonomy. Cladistics. 28 (3): 300 - 316." type="journal article" year="2012">Sauer and Hausdorf 2012</bibRefCitation>
)ı but are extremely useful for specimen identificationı especially of phenotypically similar taxa such as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nycteliusi">A. nycteliusı</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[265,417,1530,1554]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">A. valentianus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mulleri" baseAuthorityYear="1774" box="[476,613,1530,1554]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Lehmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[476,613,1530,1554]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">L. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Notablyı COI barcode analysis would also allow for distinguishing between these and other taxa non-lethally (
<bibRefCitation author="Morinha Fi Travassos Pi Carvalho Di Magalhaes Pi Cabral JAi Bastos E" box="[838,1050,1565,1589]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="99 - 101" refId="ref13337" refString="Morinha Fi Travassos Pi Carvalho Di Magalhaes Pi Cabral JAi Bastos E. 2014. DNA sampling from body swabs of terrestrial slugs (Gastropoda: Pulmonata): a simple and non-invasive method for molecular genetics approaches. J Molluscan Stud. 80 (1): 99 - 101." type="journal article" year="2014">Morinha et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) or when distal male genitalia are under-developedı as in juvenile slugs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1156,1287,1727]" lastBlockId="17.[160,1156,142,1310]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="1623" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">
Sequence analysis herein revealed distinct COI haplotypes for 
<taxonomicName box="[938,1066,1634,1658]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[938,1066,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that were not shared between species. 
<taxonomicName box="[769,1019,1669,1693]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[769,1019,1669,1693]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">Ambigolimax nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
haplotypes were more divergent than those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[589,746,1703,1727]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[589,746,1703,1727]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı corroborating findings of 
<bibRefCitation author="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="1623" pageId="16" pageNumber="1622" pagination="91907" refId="ref14178" refString="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC. 2014 a. The slugs of Britain and Ireland: undetected and undescribed species increase a well-studiedi economically important fauna by more than 20 %. PLoS One. 9 (3): e 91907." type="journal article" year="2014">Rowson et al. (2014a)</bibRefCitation>
who examined specimens collected in Europe. An 8.6% mean K2P interspecific COI divergence between the two 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[656,800,177,201]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[656,800,177,201]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species is relatively low compared to other slug species pairs (
<bibRefCitation author="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC" box="[551,784,212,236]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" pagination="91907" refId="ref14178" refString="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC. 2014 a. The slugs of Britain and Ireland: undetected and undescribed species increase a well-studiedi economically important fauna by more than 20 %. PLoS One. 9 (3): e 91907." type="journal article" year="2014">Rowson et al. 2014a</bibRefCitation>
) and is the lowest between any two limacid taxa examined in this study (
<tableCitation box="[642,727,246,270]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="14.[160,216,1434,1457]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Table 2. Estimated mean inter and intraspecific (K2P) genetic distance of COI haplotypes in eight limacid slug species. Intraspecific genetic distances are indicated in bold. Standard error estimates range from 0.013–0.025." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF44663AFFB7FFF1FF47FA1BC4F7FA22" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" tableUuid="DF44663AFFB7FFF1FF47FA1BC4F7FA22">Table 2</tableCitation>
). Howeverı 
<bibRefCitation author="Nitz Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G" box="[865,1056,246,270]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" pagination="405 - 435" refId="ref13485" refString="Nitz Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G. 2010. Inferring multiple Corsican Limax (Pulmonata: Limacidae) radiations: a combined approach using morphology and molecules. In: Burckhardt Di editor. Evolution in Action. Berlin: Springer. p. 405 - 435." type="book chapter" year="2010">Nitz et al. (2010)</bibRefCitation>
found a comparatively low K2P COI distance of 10.8% between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeusi" authorityYear="1758" box="[794,859,281,305]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Limax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[794,859,281,305]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Limax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,142,1310]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">
Both maximum likelihood and Bayesian inference analyses of COI (
<figureCitation box="[904,991,316,340]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="15.[160,225,1486,1509]" captionTargetBox="[166,1151,142,1452]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[163,1153,142,1455]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 6. Phylogram based on a SATé FastTree analysis of aligned, partial COI mtDNA sequences from selected limacid gastropod species. Specimens are represented by their GenBank accession number with the following indications: bold = COI sequence generated by this study, boxed = first sequence of A. nyctelius from a specimen collected in California, underlined = collected in New York City, asterisk = radular morphology shown in Figure 4, diamond = external phenotype shown in Figure 1, square = jaw morphology shown in Figure 2, a star within a circle = distal male genital morphology shown in Figure 5. RAxML bootstrap support values are shown above and next to nodes, and MrBayes posterior probabilities are below. Where support values are absent indicates a node that was not resolved by all analyses or a node with very low support values." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670283/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Figure 6</figureCitation>
) show all eight speciesı represented by sequence data from at least two specimensı as monophyletic. Notablyı in all analyses 
<taxonomicName box="[421,540,385,409]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[421,540,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[600,749,385,409]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[600,749,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are resolved as sister taxa. However and importantlyı taxon sampling is too poor to conclude that 
<taxonomicName box="[835,952,420,444]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[835,952,420,444]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[1008,1154,420,444]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[1008,1154,420,444]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
diverged most recently from a common ancestor. There are 15 additional described species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="(Welter-Schultes 2012)" baseAuthorityName="Welter-Schultes" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[284,658,489,513]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Lehmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[284,401,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Lehmannia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Welter-Schultes F" box="[417,650,489,513]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" refId="ref15122" refString="Welter-Schultes F. 2012. European non-marine molluscsi a guide for species identification. Goettingen: Planet Poster Editions." type="book" year="2012">Welter-Schultes 2012</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and three in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Malmi" authorityYear="1868" box="[820,953,489,513]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Malacolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[820,953,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Malacolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı all of which lack sequence data in BOLD and GenBank databases. No studyı including this oneı has examined sequence data of COI or any other molecular marker for species in other limacid generaı including six in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Boettgeri" authorityYear="1883" box="[324,464,593,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Gigantomilax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[324,464,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Gigantomilax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı seven in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simrothi" authorityYear="1902" box="[568,682,593,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Turcomilax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,682,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Turcomilax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı three in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Boettgeri" authorityYear="1881" box="[781,863,593,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Eumilax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[781,863,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Eumilax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı two in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simrothi" authorityYear="1896" box="[946,1056,593,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Metalimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[946,1056,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Metalimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı and one each in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. Hessei" authorityYear="1926" box="[242,331,627,651]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Svanetia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[242,331,627,651]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Svanetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(MolluscaBase 2018)" baseAuthorityName="MolluscaBase" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[384,719,627,651]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Caspilimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[384,497,627,651]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Caspilimax</emphasis>
(MolluscaBase 2018)
</taxonomicName>
. This lack of data makes sequence-based inference of phylogenetic relationships within and between most genera within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarcki" authorityYear="1801" box="[160,269,697,721]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Limacidae</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<emphasis box="[333,833,697,721]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">
Ambigolimaxı Lehmanniaı Malacolimaxı 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clessini" authorityYear="1887" box="[768,833,697,721]" class="Diplopoda" family="Entomobielziidae" genus="Bielzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bielzia</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
)ı and any conclusions about trait evolutionı presently untenable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,142,1310]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">
Finallyı in a literature search of the species name 
<emphasis box="[717,722,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">‘</emphasis>
valentiana 
<emphasis box="[835,841,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">’</emphasis>
or 
<emphasis box="[874,879,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">‘</emphasis>
valentianus 
<emphasis box="[1004,1010,766,790]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">’</emphasis>
referring to a limacid slugı a sample of 40 publications from 
<date box="[661,803,801,825]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" value="1999" valueMax="2018">1999 to 2018</date>
included 33 unique first authors who used the genus name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[465,607,835,859]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,607,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nine timesı 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Welter-Schultes" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[742,862,835,859]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Lehmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[742,862,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Lehmannia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
23 timesı and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeusi" authorityYear="1758" box="[1027,1091,835,859]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Limax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1027,1091,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Limax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
eight times. This generic lability reveals the need for a revision of what we refer to here as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[160,301,905,929]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[160,301,905,929]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. For exampleı our results and those reported elsewhere (
<bibRefCitation author="Klee Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G" box="[980,1150,905,929]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" pagination="13 - 16" refId="ref12597" refString="Klee Bi Falkner Gi Haszprunar G. 2005. Endemic radiations of Limax (Gastropoda: Stylommatophora) slugs in Corsica - they came twice. In: Burckhardt Di editor. Jahrestagung der Gesellschaft fur biologische Systematik [Annual Meeting of the Society for Biological Systematics] i Abstracts of talks and posters; 2005 Sept 13 - 16. Basel: Naturhistorisches Museum. p. 1 - 109." type="book chapter" year="2005">Klee et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC" box="[160,376,939,963]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" pagination="91907" refId="ref14178" refString="Rowson Bi Anderson Ri Turner JAi Symondson WOC. 2014 a. The slugs of Britain and Ireland: undetected and undescribed species increase a well-studiedi economically important fauna by more than 20 %. PLoS One. 9 (3): e 91907." type="journal article" year="2014">Rowson et al. 2014a</bibRefCitation>
) indicate that the genus 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Welter-Schultes" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[646,766,939,963]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Lehmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[646,766,939,963]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Lehmannia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not monophyletic when its name is applied to 
<taxonomicName box="[316,440,974,998]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[316,440,974,998]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and/or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[536,689,974,998]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[536,689,974,998]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionallyı 
<bibRefCitation author="Pollonera C" box="[855,1039,974,998]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref13757" refString="Pollonera C. 1887. Sulla classificazione dei Limacidi del sistema europea [On the classification of the limacids of the European system]. Bollettino dei Musei di Zoologia ed Anatomia comparata. 2 (23): 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1887">Pollonera (1887)</bibRefCitation>
proposed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[160,301,1009,1033]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[160,301,1009,1033]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for species that have a globular phallus appendixı as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[950,1102,1009,1033]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[950,1102,1009,1033]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı but not in 
<taxonomicName box="[232,350,1043,1067]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[232,350,1043,1067]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It isı thereforeı problematic that the genus name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[902,1043,1043,1067]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[902,1043,1043,1067]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is applied here and elsewhere to 
<taxonomicName box="[423,544,1078,1102]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[423,544,1078,1102]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı especially as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ferussaci" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[707,860,1078,1102]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="valentianus">
<emphasis box="[707,860,1078,1102]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. valentianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the 
<typeStatus box="[940,989,1078,1102]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus. Consequentlyı and because of the poor taxon sampling within 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">
Lehmanniaı 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Malmi" authorityYear="1868" box="[160,297,1147,1171]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Malacolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Malacolimax</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
ı and most other limacid genera (excluding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeusi" authorityYear="1758" box="[783,847,1147,1171]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Limax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[783,847,1147,1171]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Limax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)ı we recommend a revision of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[311,452,1182,1206]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[311,452,1182,1206]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
after a thorough examination of molecular and morphological data from a diversity of limacid species. A resulting taxonomy could name a new genus for 
<taxonomicName box="[160,283,1251,1275]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nyctelius">
<emphasis box="[160,283,1251,1275]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">A. nyctelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ı reject 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[370,511,1251,1275]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[370,511,1251,1275]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
altogether in favour of a new or different genusı or redescribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pollonera" authorityYear="1887" box="[259,400,1286,1310]" class="Gastropoda" family="Limacidae" genus="Ambigolimax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[259,400,1286,1310]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1623">Ambigolimax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without reference to the morphology of the phallus appendix.
</paragraph>
